# The Alessian Revolt (1E 243)

The Alessian Revolt is one of the most defining moments in the history of Tamriel. In the year 243 of the First Era, the human slaves of Cyrodiil, led by the prophetess Alessia, rose up against their Ayleid masters and founded the first human empire on the continent. This event was not merely a liberation — it redefined the metaphysical order of Mundus through the Covenant with Akatosh.

## Origins and Causes

### The Ayleid cruelty

The Ayleids, also called the Wild Elves, had ruled over Cyrodiil since the Merethic Era. Their civilization, brilliant as it was in magical and architectural terms, rested upon a system of slavery of unprecedented brutality. Ancient texts describe systematic atrocities perpetrated against the enslaved human populations.

Ayleid lords practiced what they called the "arts of torture" as a form of aesthetic expression. Human slaves were subjected to magical experiments, used in sacrificial rituals, and their suffering was regarded as a form of refined entertainment. The "flesh gardens," "intestinal sculptures," and "skin lamps" are among the horrors documented by chroniclers of the era.

### The Ayleid Daedric cult

Unlike the Altmer of Alinor, who maintained a cult to the Aedra, many Ayleid lords had turned to the worship of Daedric Princes. Meridia, Molag Bal, and other entities were venerated in their cities. This devotion to destructive forces intensified their cruelty toward mortals, as human sacrifice formed an integral part of their rituals.

Slaves thus served a dual purpose: labor force and living offerings to the Daedric Princes. This convergence of economic and ritual slavery made their condition absolutely unbearable.

### Alessia's call

Alessia, also known as Paravant, Al-Esh, or the Slave-Queen, was a slave in the Ayleid city of Sardavar Leed. According to tradition, her prayers rose to the Divines themselves. Akatosh, the Dragon of Time, heard her supplications and was moved by the suffering of her people.

But Alessia was also a remarkable political strategist. She understood that the liberation of her people required powerful allies and sent secret emissaries northward, toward the Nordic kingdoms of Skyrim.

### Internal divisions among the Ayleids

Not all Ayleid lords shared in their peers' cruelty. Some, worshippers of the Aedra rather than the Daedra, looked poorly upon the excesses of their compatriots. This internal fracture would prove decisive when the conflict came.

## The Event: The Revolt

### The divine champions

The revolt was not a simple slave uprising — it benefited from near-divine intervention. Pelinal Whitestrake, the Divine Knight, appeared as Alessia's champion. A warrior of terrifying power, he was in truth a being sent by the Divines through time itself. His murderous rages against the Ayleids were so devastating that they alarmed even his own allies.

Morihaus, the Breath of Kyne, the demi-divine son of the Nordic goddess, also joined the cause. A winged bull and formidable warrior, he became Alessia's companion and lover, symbolizing the alliance between divine forces and the human cause.

### The Nordic alliance

The Nords of Skyrim, under the leadership of their kings, answered Alessia's call. For them, fighting the Elves was both a religious duty — Shor having battled the Elves at the Dawn of Time — and a strategic opportunity to weaken a powerful neighbor. The Nordic legions provided the military expertise and manpower necessary for the revolt's success.

### The military campaign

The war was long and bloody. Pelinal led devastating assaults against Ayleid cities, reducing them one by one. His fury was such that he sometimes exterminated entire populations, drawing reproach from Morihaus himself.

The Ayleid lords loyal to the Aedra, seeing defeat as inevitable, chose to join Alessia's cause rather than perish alongside their Daedra-worshipping brethren. This internal betrayal considerably accelerated the collapse of Elvish hegemony.

### The fall of the Imperial City

The final siege focused on the White-Gold Tower, the heart of Ayleid power. Pelinal faced the most powerful Elvish champions, including Umaril the Unfeathered, champion of Meridia. Although Pelinal managed to defeat Umaril — at least his physical form — he was himself dismembered and slain by the last Ayleid lords in an act of desperate vengeance.

Despite the loss of Pelinal, the White-Gold Tower fell to Alessia's forces, marking the definitive end of Ayleid domination over Cyrodiil.

### The Covenant with Akatosh

The military victory was followed by an unprecedented metaphysical event. Akatosh manifested before Alessia and sealed a sacred covenant. The Dragon of Time poured his own blood into a jewel — the Amulet of Kings — and established the Dragonfires, a mystical barrier separating Mundus from the planes of Oblivion.

In return, Alessia's descendants and their legitimate successors were to maintain the Dragonfires burning by wearing the Amulet and receiving Akatosh's blessing. So long as this lineage endured and the fires burned, Tamriel would be protected from Daedric invasion.

## Consequences

### The First Cyrodilic Empire

Alessia became the first human Empress of Cyrodiil, founding what historians call the Alessian Empire. For the first time, humans dominated the heart of Tamriel. The Imperial City became the political center of the known world, a role it would retain for millennia.

### The religious synthesis

Alessia demonstrated remarkable political genius in matters of religion. Rather than imposing the Nordic pantheon or preserving the Elvish cults, she created a synthesis: the Eight Divines. This pantheon combined aspects of Nordic worship (Kyne becoming Kynareth, Shor becoming Shezarr) with Elvish elements (Auri-El becoming Akatosh), enabling unity among the different populations of her empire.

### The fate of the Ayleids

The Ayleids who had fought against Alessia were exterminated or driven out. Those who had supported her initially received territories and a degree of autonomy. However, in the centuries that followed, the Alessian Order — a human supremacist religious movement — systematically persecuted all remaining Ayleids, leading to the complete extinction of their race in Tamriel.

### The Dragonfires and the protection of Mundus

The Dragonfire system became the cornerstone of Tamriel's existential security. As long as a legitimate emperor wore the Amulet of Kings and maintained the fires, the Daedric Princes could not physically invade Mundus. This protection would endure until the end of the Third Era, during the Oblivion Crisis.

### The political legacy

The very concept of "Empire" as it would exist across the ages — Reman, Septim — finds its origin in Alessia's founding act. The idea that a legitimate ruler, blessed by Akatosh, could unify and protect the peoples of Tamriel would remain the ideological foundation of all subsequent imperial dynasties.

